define concurrent capture behavior explicitly. Either require a repo/GitMeta capture lock, or require post-transaction conflict detection/retry around the dedupe read.\n\n4. **Skipping turn creation when zero new records makes retry recovery impossible in one important case.**  \n   The spec notices “records write succeeds, turn write fails,” but the current direction still says “create only when new records exist.” Once old partial data exists, retry sees zero new records and has no record set to derive the missing turn key. Spec tweak: store a capture-batch marker or pending accepted-record set in the same transaction, or define a repair path that can backfill a missing turn from transcript entries written after the previous turn.\n\n5. **`previous_turn_key` is underspecified under concurrent or out-of-order capture.**  \n   “Previous capture turn in the same session” sounds simple, but capture timestamp, GitMeta list order, and provider source index can disagree. Spec tweak: define previous as “latest committed turn summary for this session before applying this capture transaction, ordered by turn-list append order,” and say concurrent captures must retry if previous changed.\n\n6. **Backfill as one giant turn is product-clean but implementation-painful.**  \n   First capture of a long transcript could store hundreds/thousands of records plus one environment snapshot that falsely represents all of them. That’s acceptable if called out as weak evidence. Spec tweak: add `capture_kind: \"backfill\" | \"incremental\"` and maybe `record_count` thresholds. Scoring should heavily downrank environment evidence on backfill turns.\n\n7. **Environment snapshot cost is hand-waved.**  \n   Using `but_api::diff::changes_in_worktree` is not “just paths”; it computes assignments and dependencies: [diff.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-api/src/diff.rs:130). That is too expensive and side-effecty for every stop hook. Spec tweak: require a path-only snapshot API, probably below `but-api`, that avoids hunk assignment, dependency calculation, line stats, and UI diff materialization.\n\n8. **Commit file collection can explode on stacked workspaces.**  \n   “All commits in each branch” plus tree-delta per commit is scary in large stacks or old branches. Spec tweak: cap commits per branch or capture only commits in the workspace/stack presentation window. Store `commit_count`, `commits_truncated`, and maybe `commit_files_status`.\n\n9. **Index staleness is okay, but versioning alone is not enough.**  \n   The doc says no deletion/rebuild in v1 and readers verify candidates. Fine. But old index keys still bloat sync forever, and key canonicalization mistakes become permanent clutter. Spec tweak: add `gitbutler:agentlog-index:active-version = v1` and make index values include an `index_schema` or encode one canonical JSON payload, not ad hoc `session/turn` strings.\n\n10. **Index value shape is ambiguous.**  \n   `set<session-key/turn-key>` needs escaping rules. Slashes are probably fine as values, but don’t make readers parse a mini-format. Spec tweak: use JSON string values or a delimiter-free fixed shape like `{session_key}\\0{turn_key}` only if GitMeta set values handle NUL safely. I’d pick compact JSON for sanity.\n\n11. **Branch/review keys need canonicalization now, not later.**  \n   Branch names can be local, remote, fully qualified, Unicode, case-sensitive, renamed, or stack segment aliases. PR numbers are forge-scoped, not globally meaningful. Spec tweak: define keys like `branch:<sha256(refname bytes)>`, `review:github:<owner>/<repo>#<number>` or explicitly repo-local `github-pr:<number>` with the limitation documented.\n\n12. **Plain Git mode assumption is risky.**  \n   The doc says use the same workspace/head-info path and avoid a fallback unless needed. That’s optimism wearing a fake mustache. Spec tweak: define the v1 fallback shape now: one synthetic stack, current branch if any, HEAD commits if bounded, detached-head allowed, no review metadata.\n\n13. **Provider turn grouping needs parser changes before storage design is final.**  \n   Current parsed records don’t carry provider turn ids; they only keep generic source data and hash/index fields. Spec tweak: define `provider_turn_key` production per provider and whether it is hashed from raw provider id, source path + id, or event boundary.\n\n14. **Future scoring needs more negative evidence fields.**  \n   The scoring section is good, but the storage model lacks enough “how incomplete was this?” metadata. Spec tweak: add reasoned statuses per sub-observation: `worktree.status`, `stacks.status`, `commit_files.status`, each with `complete|partial|failed|skipped`, plus counts/truncation. One top-level `partial` is too blunt.\n\n15. **Sync/retry lifecycle is underdescribed.**  \n   Hook capture spawns async sync and discards output: [cli.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs:123). Local capture can succeed while remote GitMeta sync fails for a long time. Spec tweak: separate local capture durability from remote sync state. Add `last_local_capture_at`; don’t imply review sharing can see turns until sync succeeds.\n\n**Spec Tweaks I’d Make**\n\n- Add `capture_kind`, `capture_sequence`, and `previous_turn_key` semantics.\n- Require a capture-level lock or explicit optimistic retry loop around dedupe + previous-turn lookup + write.\n- Move all capture writes into one `apply_edits` call; no stray `handle.set*`.\n- Define a path-only environment snapshot API and ban UI diff/hunk assignment from hook capture.\n- Add caps for commits and branches, not just file paths.\n- Make backfill environment evidence weak by schema, not just scoring convention.\n- Canonicalize branch/review/change index keys in the spec.\n- Add per-section snapshot statuses and truncation fields.\n- Define index value encoding concretely.\n- Add a v1 plain-Git fallback shape instead of discovering that hole mid-implementation.\n\nBlunt take: the model is good, but the spec currently reads like storage is the hard part. It isn’t. The hard part is making stop-hook capture cheap, idempotent, retryable, and not quietly wrong when the workspace graph is weird.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:15:45.388Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}